#compdef svgo-viewbox
# ============================================================================
# svgo-viewbox - add viewBox attribute to SVG
#                 files + optimize them with SVGO
#                 in one pass (Node.js, MIT)
#
# Author : Atanas Atanasov (scriptex)
# Upstream: https://github.com/scriptex/svgo-viewbox
# npm    : svgo-viewbox (binary: svgo-viewbox)
#
# `svgo-viewbox` is a small Node CLI that walks a
# directory of SVG files, computes + adds a `viewBox`
# attribute to each (using `svgo-add-viewbox`), then
# runs the standard SVGO optimization pipeline over
# the result. The combined operation is useful for
# SVG icon libraries / asset pipelines where source
# SVGs lack viewBox declarations (so they render
# at fixed pixel sizes instead of scaling) + need
# to be optimized for production.
#
# The viewBox + optimize combination is critical
# for responsive icon systems:
#   - Without viewBox: SVG renders at fixed
#     width/height (e.g. 24x24 pixels) regardless
#     of CSS sizing - icons appear cropped or
#     squashed at non-native sizes
#   - With viewBox: SVG renders at any size via
#     CSS width/height + maintains aspect ratio
#   - With SVGO optimization: SVG file size is
#     typically reduced by 30-60% via dead-code
#     removal, attribute coalescing, path
#     simplification
#
# Use cases:
#   - Build-time SVG icon library preparation
#     (Lucide-style icon set generation)
#   - Asset pipeline pre-processing in static-site
#     generators
#   - Post-processing SVGs exported from Illustrator/
#     Sketch/Figma that lack viewBox
#   - One-shot batch processing of an entire SVG
#     directory
#
# Usage:
#   svgo-viewbox -i <input-dir> [-f <svgo-config>]
#
# Flags (meow v14 declarative flags):
#   -i, --input <dir>          - path to folder
#                                 containing SVG
#                                 files to process
#                                 (required)
#   -f, --svgo-file <path>     - path to SVGO
#                                 configuration
#                                 file in JS format
#                                 (see https://
#                                 github.com/svg/
#                                 svgo#configuration
#                                 for SVGO config
#                                 schema; default
#                                 is SVGO's built-
#                                 in defaults +
#                                 the svgo-add-
#                                 viewbox plugin)
#   --help                     - print meow help
#                                 + exit
#   --version                  - print version +
#                                 exit
#
# Examples:
#   svgo-viewbox --input ./assets/images/svg \
#                --svgo-file ./svgo.config.js
#   svgo-viewbox -i ./icons -f ./svgo.config.mjs
#
# Example svgo.config.js:
#   export default {
#     multipass: true,
#     plugins: [
#       'preset-default',
#       'removeDimensions',
#       'removeRasterImages',
#     ]
#   }
#
# The svgo lane is built on `svgo ^4.0.1` (declared
# at upstream package.json HEAD as a direct dep,
# with `peerDependencies: { svgo: "^3.0.0 || ^4.0.0" }`
# also declared, imported as
# `import { optimize, loadConfig } from 'svgo'` in
# index.mjs, then `optimize(svgString,
# updatedConfig)` for the file optimization step
# + `loadConfig(svgoFile)` for loading the user-
# supplied SVGO config), the canonical Node SVG
# optimization library by the svg/svgo team
# (lead by Sergey Belov / strarsis / Lev Solntsev) -
# github.com/svg/svgo.
#
# `svgo` (SVG Optimizer) is the de-facto canonical
# Node SVG optimization library:
#   - Plugin-based architecture (35+ built-in
#     plugins for various SVG transformations)
#   - Default preset (`preset-default`) runs the
#     30 most commonly useful optimizations
#   - Loaded from a JS config file (.svgo.config.
#     js/.svgo.config.mjs) with full Node API
#     access for dynamic plugin configuration
#   - Used by 50,000+ npm packages including:
#     - webpack svgo-loader + svgo-loader plugin
#     - vite-plugin-svgo
#     - vite-svg-loader
#     - parcel SVGO transform
#     - rollup-plugin-svgo
#     - svgr (SVG-to-React-component) uses svgo
#       for source SVG cleanup
#     - imagemin-svgo (imagemin plugin)
#     - Material Design Icons + Lucide + Heroicons
#       + most icon libraries process their SVGs
#       through svgo at build time
#     - Storybook
#     - Next.js + Nuxt.js + Gatsby + Astro
#       (default SVG processing pipelines)
#     - Hugo + Jekyll + 11ty (SVG asset processing)
#
# svgo's distinguishing features:
#   - SVGO v3 → v4 transition (the v4 API is
#     async-first + ESM-first; v3 was sync + CJS)
#   - Built-in plugins span every aspect of SVG
#     optimization:
#     - removeXMLProcInstructions
#     - removeDoctype
#     - removeMetadata
#     - removeXMLNS
#     - removeEditorsNSData (Illustrator/Inkscape
#       metadata)
#     - cleanupAttrs (whitespace + duplicate
#       cleanup)
#     - cleanupNumericValues (precision reduction)
#     - cleanupListOfValues (path data precision)
#     - convertColors (hex → 3-char hex, RGB →
#       hex, named colors)
#     - convertPathData (path command optimization)
#     - convertTransform (matrix simplification)
#     - removeUselessStrokeAndFill
#     - removeUnusedNS
#     - cleanupIds (rename IDs to short names)
#     - removeRasterImages (strip embedded PNGs)
#     - mergePaths (combine same-style paths)
#     - removeDimensions (strip width/height in
#       favor of viewBox)
#     - removeAttributesBySelector
#     - removeStyleElement / removeScriptElement
#     - inlineStyles (move <style> rules to
#       attributes)
#     - reusePaths (extract duplicates to <defs>)
#   - Plugin overrides via the `params` field
#     in config
#   - `multipass: true` runs optimizations
#     iteratively until no further reduction
#
# The svg/svgo organization governance:
#   - Founded by Sergey Belov + the russian
#     frontend community in 2012
#   - Maintained by an active multi-maintainer
#     team (Lev Solntsev, Sergei Skorbatyuk,
#     Ivan Yaremko, Vladimir Kuznetsov, et al.)
#   - org-backed multi-maintainer model with
#     continuity through contributor churn
#   - The v3 → v4 transition demonstrates active
#     development + spec compliance updates
#
# svgo's foundational position in the Node SVG
# ecosystem mirrors:
#   - js-yaml (Vitaly Puzrin / nodeca) in YAML
#     parsing
#   - markdown-it (Vitaly Puzrin / markdown-it
#     org) in Markdown parsing
#   - undici (Matteo Collina) in HTTP
#   - postcss (Andrey Sitnik) in CSS processing
#   - node-glob (Isaac Z. Schlueter) in globbing
#
# These multi-maintainer-org canonical libraries
# form the substrate of the Node ecosystem -
# nearly every modern web-development build
# pipeline transitively depends on at least 3-5
# of them.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 264 :: SVG rendering libraries (parse +
#              rasterize/render SVG documents
#              following the W3C SVG 1.1/2.0
#              specification)
# Round 1492 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 264
#                                       (257th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : linebender/resvg            [R1490 _oxdraw]
#             (Yevhenii Reizner; parse +
#              rasterize)
#   Go      : ajstarks/svgo               [R1491 _processd]
#             (Anthony Starks; generate
#              only)
#   TS/Node : svg/svgo                    [R1492 THIS FILE]
#             (Sergey Belov + svgo team;
#              optimize/transform; not
#              parse-render)
#
# svg/svgo closes Axis 264 with the *optimize-
# only* canonical pattern. The three lanes form
# a clean spectrum of SVG-library specialization:
#
#   - Rust (resvg): parse + render (rasterize to
#     PNG); no generation; no optimization
#   - Go (ajstarks/svgo): generate (write SVG
#     XML); no parsing; no rendering; no
#     optimization
#   - Node (svg/svgo): parse + optimize +
#     re-serialize; no rasterization
#
# Each lane fills a *different* role in the SVG
# pipeline. There is no single library that
# spans the full SVG pipeline in any language
# ecosystem - parsing, manipulation, generation,
# optimization, and rasterization are
# specialization splits that reflect SVG's
# enormous spec surface:
#   - SVG 1.1: ~600 page W3C recommendation
#   - SVG 2: ~800 page draft + still
#     unimplemented features
#   - CSS integration: SVG can use the full CSS
#     properties model
#   - Scripting: SMIL animation + SVG-native
#     scripting hooks
#   - Filter primitives: dozens of filter
#     effects (Gaussian blur, color matrices,
#     turbulence, displacement maps, lighting,
#     compositing, morphology, ...)
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the SVG
# document level - svgo-optimized SVG can be
# parsed by resvg (Rust) + svgo (Node again,
# circular) + librsvg + Inkscape + any compliant
# SVG parser. The W3C SVG XML grammar is the
# lingua franca.
#
# Notable that Axis 264 is the *most-fragmented*
# axis in the corpus by specialization split -
# the SVG ecosystem has no canonical full-stack
# library in any language, only specialists. This
# reflects SVG's position as a *document format*
# (like Markdown/YAML) rather than a *data format*
# (like JSON/CBOR) - document formats accumulate
# tooling specialization over time as use cases
# diversify.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Node author/org cohort
# (now spanning 11 distinct individuals/orgs):
#   - Sindre Sorhus (chalk + ~1000 microlibs)
#   - Matt Ranney + Redis Inc. (node-redis)
#   - Brian Carlson (node-postgres)
#   - Andrey Sitnik (PostCSS + browserslist +
#     nanoid)
#   - Lovell Fuller (sharp)
#   - Paul Miller (noble umbrella)
#   - Devon Govett (foliojs umbrella +
#     lightningcss)
#   - Matteo Collina (undici + pino + fastify)
#   - Isaac Z. Schlueter (npm CLI + node-glob +
#     rimraf + node-semver)
#   - Vitaly Puzrin + nodeca (js-yaml +
#     markdown-it + pako + argparse + sax +
#     linkify-it)
#   - Sergey Belov + svgo team (svg/svgo, THIS
#     AXIS)
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - oxdraw (Rust, resvg + tiny-skia): Mermaid-
#     style diagram CLI; parses Mermaid + renders
#     to SVG/PNG via resvg pipeline
#   - processd (Go, ajstarks/svgo): Minecraft
#     avatar processor; generates SVG views of
#     skin textures via svgo's procedural API
#   - svgo-viewbox (Node, svg/svgo + svgo-add-
#     viewbox): batch SVG viewBox-adder +
#     optimizer; uses svgo for the optimization
#     phase
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (diagram
# rendering / avatar generation / asset-pipeline
# optimization), three implementation strategies
# (full-stack pure-Rust / generation-only Go /
# parse+optimize Node), all converging on the
# W3C SVG XML grammar.
#
# Axis 264 closes the round 1492 cycle - 257th
# axis closed total. The three lanes
# collectively demonstrate that SVG is *the most
# specialization-fragmented format axis* in the
# corpus, with no single library spanning the
# full pipeline in any ecosystem - a structural
# pattern unique to document formats with vast
# spec surface.
# ============================================================================

_svgo-viewbox() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-i --input)'{-i,--input}'[path to folder containing SVG files]:dir:_files -/' \
        '(-f --svgo-file)'{-f,--svgo-file}'[path to SVGO configuration file in JS format]:file:_files -g "*.(js|mjs|cjs)"' \
        '(- *)--help[print help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]'
}

_svgo-viewbox "$@"
